Rating: 3
Having eaten many tagines in Morocco, I'd say that this rendition isn't bad at all! Helps if you have the special, conical-shaped cooking vessel from which this type of dish takes its name. In Morocco, the tagine is served beside (not over) the couscous, which is often flavoured with tangerine juice or orange blossom water. Slow simmering is key to allow the fat on the meat to melt into the pot, yeilding an unctiously tender, falling apart piece of meat. try toasting the raisins and almonds together before adding to the dish near the end.

