A substitute for saffron is tumeric.

Rating: 0
Saffron's flavor is hard to describe, it's very pungent and aromatic. You should be able to find saffron in the spice aisle of most large supermarkets, but be sure to get threads and not powder. Often the powder is adulterated with turmeric to extend it, as it has a similar color. As for the res-al-hanout, just from reading the description of the stuff (50 different spices?!) I doubt there's a good substitute. I suppose you could try garam masala, but you might have to go to an Indian market to find it as it's not as common as the saffron.

